  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime in most countries around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or other criminal activities) appear legitimate by funneling it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to disguise the illicit origin of the funds and integrate them into the legitimate financial system.\n\nLaws against money laundering are designed to combat organized crime, terrorism financing, and other illegal activities that rely on the disguising of unlawfully obtained funds. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment. International cooperation and regulations, such as those established by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), aim to combat money laundering globally.",
